 Accepted 11 November 1997 
 
 Abstract 
 Previous scientific studies of multiple job holding have tended to focus on the (features/ qualities/ traits) of those getting off-fann employment 
 and the factors affecting the hours supplied to those getting off-farm activities. None of these studies have clearly talked to/looked at the reasons 
 behind the decision to look (for)  off-farm employment. Neither have they been able to examine in-depth the important issue of how this major 
 part of the farm part/area responds to alternative policies, since most studies have used thin sliceal data for a given area. A 
 comparison between countries would permit the analysis of how multiple job holding responds to different government policies. The 
 purpose of this paper is to examine the reasons for and factors affecting multiple job holdings of dairy farm families in close-by areas 
 of two counties, United States and Canada. The bordering areas of New York and Ontario have almost the same  (land-area-based/location) conditions but 
 very different farm support and social service policies. The results point to/show the importance of farm income on why people work off 
 the farm and provide (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of multiple job holding as a flexible (machine/method/way) for dealing with changes in the money-based (surrounding conditions) facing 
 the household. For operators, the driving (features/ qualities/ traits) influencing off-farm labor participation is the farm's (money-related) position. The 
 supply-managed milk marketing system secures/makes sure of higher and more stable returns for Ontario dairy farm labor. In contrast, it is family 
 (information about people/combinations of different kinds of people), educational level and social support policy that appears to mostly influence (related to a husband or wife) off-farm employment decisions. Free 
 medical care in Ontario lowers the reservation wage for household members. The effect of these farm and social support policies on the 
 relative returns to labor in farming and non-farm employment explains the lower participation rate and hours supplied in off-farm work 
 by both operators, and hours supplied in off-farm work by both operators and (husband or wife)s in Ontario dairy farm household. Published by 
 Elsevier Science B.V. 
 Keywords: Multiple job holding; Dairy farm; New York; Ontario 
 
 1. Introduction 
 Rising nonfarm wages and a greater increase in the supply of farming-based products relative to demand has 
 depressed farm earnings for some families in the nonfarm part/area over the last few 20 years. The resulting 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) of labor out of farming has happened through a large reduction in the number of farms, and also 
 through dual employment of those remaining on the farm (Huffman, 1991). Multiple job holding may be viewed 
 
 ' Corresponding author. 
 0169-5150/98/$19.00 Published by Elsevier Science B.V. 
 PII S0169-5!50(97)00053-4 
 
 128 
 
 A. Weersink et al. /Agricultural Money flow 18 (1998) 127-143 
 
 as a (lasting for a short time) thing/event in response to (money-related) pressures in farming, but it has always been present 
 (Fuller, 1991). Over the last few years, almost 60% of US farm families had either the (husband or wife), operator, or both 
 employed in off-farm work and about 80% had higher cash incomes from off-farm earnings (including 
 wages, rent, interest etc.) than from their farm (USDA, 1992). 
 The reasons for examining multiple job holding are usually grouped into 3 issues (Carlin and Bentley, 
 1991). First are (related to workers in general) issues surrounding (wasting very little while working or producing something) and equity differences between those working 
 full-time on the farm and those with off-farm jobs. If the last thing just mentioned group are less productive, then understanding the 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) of those people would aid in targeting extension efforts to help improve their (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 However, the need for such efforts and for other farm programs such as income support are brought into 
 question if total household income for multiple job holding farm families is just like those families without 
 off-farm jobs. Second are (away from cities) development issues that are related to the equity (things to carefully think about) just talked about/said. 
 If total family incomes are greater for families with off-farm jobs, then the richness of areas away from cities may be 
 improved more through efforts to increase non-farm employment opportunities than through direct income 
 support to farmers. Third are forecasts related to farm structure. The (popular thing/general way things are going) to a bi-modal distribution of farm 
 sizes is supported if multiple job holding people (who were part of a study, etc.) tend to be middle-(old/allowed to get old/got older). Such people are unlikely to 
 view off-farm work as a (lasting for a short time) phase in a change to full-time farming, but rather as a full-time occupation 
 with farming as a sideline activity. Operators whose major occupation is not farming almost only have 
 small farms (USDA, 1992). A bi-modal distribution has effects/results/suggestions for issues such as research (things that are important), (away from cities) 
 (set of machines), (money-related) servicess, and agri-food processing location decisions (Goddard et al., 1993). 
 Previous scientific studies of multiple job holding have tended to focus on the (features/ qualities/ traits) of those 
 getting off-farm employment and the factors affecting the hours supplied to those off-farm activities (e.g., 
 Bollman, 1979; Huffman, 1980; Sumner, 1982; Simpson and Kapitany, 1983; Gould and Saupe, 1989; Huffman 
 and Lange, 1989; Woman  et al., 1988; Woman  and Gempesaw, 1992; and Weersink, 1992). Focus has been on human 
 capital (features/ qualities/ traits) with the general finding that the increasing off-farm employment rate is due to changes in 
 not important returns to labor between off-farm and farm activities arising mostly from improved workers 
 skills. None of these studies have clearly talked to/looked at the reasons behind the decision to look (for)  off-farm 
 employment. Neither have they been able to examine in-depth the important issue of how this major part 
 of the farm part/area responds to alternative policies (Sumner, 1991), since most studies have used thin sliceal 
 data for a given area. A comparison between countries would permit the analysis of how multiple job holding 
 responds to different government policies. 
 The purpose of this paper is to examine the reasons for and factors affecting multiple job holdings of dairy 
 farm families in close-by areas of two counties, United States and Canada. The bordering areas of New 
 York and Ontario have almost the same  (land-area-based/location) conditions but very different farm support and social service 
 policies. Milk production in Ontario is controlled through a supply management system that enables producers 
 in that area of control/area of land to earn higher and more stable returns than their partners in New York for whom milk 
 prices are subject to a greater degree of market forces. Families in Ontario also benefit from free access to 
 medical care but pay higher taxes. The lack of such coverage for families in New York can be a reason for a 
 member of a farm household to look (for)  off-farm employment in order to get fringe benefits such as medical 
 insurance (Jensen and Salant, 1985, Alwang and Stallmann, 1992). The different forms of government 
 support in the two areas and the focus on dairy, which needs/demands more labor loyalty to/promise to the farm than other 
 farming-based products, should permit ideas of how off-farm labor decisions are affected by government 
 policy. 
 The paper begins with a possible model of multiple job holding decisions by farm families followed by the 
 econometric means of guessing the model that accounts for joint decision-making and self-selection biases. 
 Section 2 of the paper examines differences between the two areas in the extent of multiple job holdings and 
 its explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) along with a discussion of how policy has added/has given to these differences. We then 
 carefully study (wasting very little while working or producing something) and equity measures for different work governments and factors affecting the decision to 
 participate in off-farm work. First (or most important) reasons for multiple job holdings given by the household and their 
 
 A. Weersink et al.j Farming-based Money flow 18 ( 1998) 127-143 
 
 129 
 
 relationship to farm income are then examined. Finally, factors affecting both demand and supply for off-farm 
 labor are discussed. Differences in off-farm employment patterns between New York and Ontario as partial 
 indicators of how different government policies affect multiple job holding decisions by dairy farm families 
 are focused on. 
 
 2. Possible model 
 The decision to work off-farm by operators and (husband or wife)s can be viewed through an farming-based household 
 model that combines farming-based production, consumption and labor supply decisions into a single (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built). 
 Almost the same  models have been used by Huffman and Lange (1989), Gould and Saupe (1989), and Woman  and 
 Gempesaw (1992). In these models, the household is assumed to (make as big as possible) utility by using/eating different 
 valuable things that it produces by combining market products (that are bought and sold)  and time. Household utility is assumed to be received/made from 
 from consumption of all products (that are bought and sold) (G) and fun time for the operator (L0 ) and (husband or wife) (L8 ). The level of utility 
 came/coming from (bought something for money) products (that are bought and sold)  and fun is affected by (coming from the outside of something) (numbers that change/things that change) such as workers (features/ qualities/ traits) of the operator (H 0 ) and (husband or wife) (H 8 ) along with other household and area (features/ qualities/ traits) such as number 
 and age distribution of children and service availability (ZH). 
 
 ( 1) 
 Utility is (made as big as possible) subject to restrictions on time, income and farm working well. Time for the operator and 
 (husband or wife) are assumed to be blended. Each set apart their total time gift (T) to either fun (L) or 
 work which consists of time spent working on the farm (F) and possibly in off-farm employment (M). It is 
 assumed that a positive amount of time is set apart and given out to fun and farm work, but that hours of off-farm work 
 may be zero for either the operator or (husband or wife). 
 
 (2) 
 Working on or off the farm is done to create income for (instance of buying something for money) of consumption products (that are bought and sold)  bought at a price 
 Pa. Total amount spent on products (that are bought and sold)  for direct or indirect consumption is limited by the amount earned from farm 
 
 income, off-farm income and other (coming from the outside of something) household income (V). Assuming the household faces perfectly 
 competitive output and input markets, farm income (PQQ- RX) is equal to the price of farm output (PQ) 
 multiplied by amount produced (Q) less (number or thing that changes) costs of production RX where R is the input price vector, and 
 X is the amount of (bought) farm inputs. Off-farm income is the product of the wage rate (W) and the hours 
 worked off-farm by both the operator and (husband or wife) (W 0 M 0 + W 8 M 8 ). The budget restriction on household 
 income is therefore 
 
 (3) 
 The wage rates facing operators and (husband or wife)s are assumed to depend on their (pertaining to each person or thing) workers 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) (H) and local labor market conditions (ZM). 
 
 (4) 
 While off-farm wage rates are assumed to be independent of the hours worked, not important returns to farm 
 labor by the operator and (husband or wife) are assumed to reduce with increases in hours of farm work. The production 
 function therefore orders/forces an added/more restriction on utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) by the household. Farm production 
 technology is represented by 
