 where j(.) is a strictly curved production function and ZF is a vector of (coming from the outside of something) farm specific 
 (features/ qualities/ traits). Workers (features/ qualities/ traits) are included in the production function to account for the increased 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) assumed to be related to factors such as years of formal education and prior farming experience. 
 The household (makes as big as possible) utility (1) subject to its time (2), budget (3) and farm working well (5) restrictions 
 through its choice of consumption products (that are bought and sold)  (bought something for money), amount of farm inputs (bought something for money), and the work hours of 
 the operator and (husband or wife) gave out to farm and off-farm employment. Best levels of these choice (numbers that change/things that change) 
 can be figured out by/decided by (at the same time) solving the first-order conditions (see Huffman, 1991). An interior 
 solution is assumed for all choice (numbers that change/things that change) with the exception of off-farm work by both the operator and 
 (husband or wife). Best hours of off-farm work are zero if the not important return to off-farm labor or wage rate (W) is 
 less than the not important value of farm labor tested at the point of best time portion between farm work 
 and fun and with no off-farm work. The not important value of farm labor is the product of farm output price 
 (PQ) and the not important product of farm labor (JF(.)). If, at this point, not important returns to off-farm labor are 
 greater than farm work, the individual will increase off-farm work hours, by that/in that way increasing the not important value 
 of farm labor until the not important returns to both forms of employment are equaled the tax rate of 
 substitution between fun and consumption products (that are bought and sold) (W = PQJF(.) = UL/ U0 ). 
 Given the idea (you think is true) that the farm household is a price taker in output and input markets, the household 
 model is recursive if an interior solution exists for all choice (numbers that change/things that change). Decisions on farm labor and (bought something for money) 
 inputs are first made, and then consumption decisions on (bought) products (that are bought and sold)  and fun. Off-farm labor supply 
 functions are received/made from leftover/extraly from the time restriction and will contain all (coming from the outside of something) (numbers that change/things that change) in the 
 held back optimization problem. 
 
 (6) 
 However, if best hours of off-farm work are zero for either the operator or (husband or wife), household decisions 
 (related to/looking at/thinking about) farm production and consumption decisions must be made both/together, rather than recursively. Off-farm 
 labor supply is still decided/figured out leftover/extraly as function of the same (numbers that change/things that change) in Eq. (6), except that the 
 unobservable wage rate for an individual not working off-farm is not a (thing that decides something) of the hours worked 
 off-farm by the other partner. However, the supply function for this partner is (may or may not happen, depending on something) upon the participation 
 decision by the partner without off-farm employment. 
 
 3. Econometric model 
 The approach for guessing the model of multiple job holdings just presented is based on Huffman and 
 Lange (1989) and involves guessing the demand for off-farm labor and the supply of this labor by both the 
 operator and the (husband or wife). These decisions on off-farm employment for both members are made both/together by the 
 household and can result in four possible pictures/situations: (1) both operator and (husband or wife) work off-farm (M 0 &amp;gt; 0, 
 Ms &amp;gt; 0); (2) only the operator works off-farm (M 0 &amp;gt; 0, Ms = 0); only the (husband or wife) has off-farm employment 
 (M 0 = 0, Ms &amp;gt; 0); and (4) neither partner works off-farm (M 0 = 0, Ms = 0). These four governments, which will 
 be represented by the subscript j later, have been (match up each pair of items in order) classified as: dual career, traditional part-time, dual 
 career part-time, and traditional (Deseran et al., 1984). 
