 The chance of working off-farm represented by Eqs. (10) and (11) for the operator and (husband or wife), (match up each pair of items in order), 
 is equal to the chance of the wage rate being greater than the reservation wage. This chance can be 
 rotten into two (may or may not happen, depending on something) chances depending on the size of their partner's off-farm earning rate and 
 reservation wage, and in turn the chance of their partner working on or off the farm. Such combined participation 
 decisions can be guessed with a bivariate probit model. 
 The connected nature of the wage and hours worked equations hints that the (may or may not happen, depending on something) means of the 
 disturbance terms in these equations are unlikely to be zero. The biases can be corrected by creating new 
 (numbers that change/things that change) from the bivariate probit equations that are (may or may not happen, depending on something) means of the disturbance terms and substituting 
 them into the demand and supply equations (Amemiya, 1974; Fishe et al., 1981; Gould and Saupe, 1989; 
 Huffman and Lange, 1989). For example, the off-farm labor demand Eq. (7) is changed to the following: 
 
