 4. Data 
 Data used in the analysis were gotten from a May 1991 survey of dairy farm families in four nearby areas 
 in New York and Ontario, with two areas in each state/province. A random sample of 500 dairy farms from 
 northern and western counties in New York was given by the New York Farming-based Statistics Service. The 
 Ontario sample was drawn for two areas (related to scientific farming)ally almost the same as  the two in New York. One consisted of five 
 counties in eastern Ontario across the St. Lawerence River from the northern New York area and the other 
 consisted of three counties in southwestern Ontario due west of the western New York area. Southwestern 
 Ontario and western New York tend to have more productive farmland and more good (related to the Earth's weather) conditions, 
 and so a more (many different kinds of people or things) farming-based part/area than the other two areas. A random sample of 220 producers from 
 eastern Ontario and 304 from southwestern Ontario was created from the Ontario Milk Marketing Board's 
 computerized information file. Overall response rate was 29.4% for New York and 40.9% for Ontario. Although 
 response rates were (compared to other things) low due to the spring timing of the survey, sample biases were not thought of as a 
 problem based on a comparison of person who responded (features/ qualities/ traits) such as farm size, working well and operator age to 
 those from other published sources (authors). 
 The demand and supply of off-farm labor are influenced by four general categories of (numbers that change/things that change); household or 
 family (features/ qualities/ traits) (ZH), workers (features/ qualities/ traits) (H), farm (features/ qualities/ traits) (Zp) and local labor market 
 condition (ZM). Means, standard mistakes and the units of measurement for the explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) are 
 given by area in Table 1 and under the four possible work governments (j) in Table 2. 
 Family (features/ qualities/ traits) include the number of children in different age categories and the level of happiness 
 the family has with farm life. The effect of children on off-farm employment decisions was measured by the 
 number of children in each of three different age categories (less than 6, between 6-ll, and between 12-18). 
 Increases in the number of preschool age children is guessed to decrease the chance of off-farm 
 employment especially for (husband or wife)s. In contrast, time demands may decrease and expenses increase for older 
 children, suggesting a greater chance of the operator or (husband or wife) looking (for) employment outside the farm. Dairy 
 farm families in each area were asked about their level of happiness using a Likert scale with 1 being very 
 made happy and 5 representing very dissatisfied. The more content people are with their situation on the farm, 
 the less likely they are to desire off-farm employment. 
 Workers (features/ qualities/ traits) include age, education and farm experience. The effect of age on off-farm 
 employment is confusing, since both farm and off-farm labor working well are assumed to increase with 
 
