 experience as measured by age. To account for possible life cycle produces, age is also included in quadratic form. 
 As with age, education has a almost the same  good  confusing effect on off-farm labor supply. However, most 
 previous studies have found education to have a larger effect on market earnings than on the not important value of 
 farm labor, by that/in that way increasing the chance of participation and off-farm employment hours. Education is 
 measured through seven categories for the highest level of education received/got, ranging from some grade school 
 to college graduate. 
 Farm (features/ qualities/ traits) will influence the value of farm labor working well. Farm labor (F) along with (bought) 
 inputs X decides/figures out farm output Q. Since the level of farm inputs and off-farm labor hours are serious and stubborn 
 (at the same time), farm output cannot be included in the guess off-farm participation and supply equations 
 unless it is guessed and the (described the future) values incorporated (Huffman, 1980). Although off-farm employment 
 decisions are made (at the same time) with the portion of farm inputs, some inputs can be assumed to be fixed 
 for farms in a single thin slice (Gould and Saupe, 1989). Fixed factors thought about/believed in this study were the 
 number of good areas of land and herd size. It is guessed that increases in these size (numbers that change/things that change) will increase 
 not important returns to farm labor and in that way decrease the chance of off-farm work and hours of such work 
 supplied. Added/more farm (features/ qualities/ traits) focused on the firm's (money-related) position. Decreases in net farm income 
 may cause the need for off-farm income to meet a desired level of total household income. The need for 
 off-farm employment may also increase with the level of (money-related) responsibilities which was measured by the 
 debt-to-valuable thing ratio (Simpson and Kapitany, 1983). 
 Local labor market conditions influence the availability of off-farm employment and wage rate. Access to 
 employment opportunities was measured by distance to the nearest town providing emergency medical services. 
 A binary (number or thing that changes) for state or area of control/area of land (New York or Ontario) in which the farm was located was also included 
 to (take control of) differences in labor market conditions and in policies between the two countries that may affect 
 off-farm employment decisions not (taken/took control of) by previous (numbers that change/things that change). It is guessed that families in New 
 York are more likely to look (for)  work off the farm due to the lower degree of farm and social support from the 
 government that by that/in that way lowers the not important value product to labor on the farm. Also, a (related to a large area) binary 
 (number or thing that changes) was also included (eastjnorth or western). Increased employment opportunities and so higher wages 
 are assumed to exist in the more populated western areas of both areas. 
