 5. Results 
 5.1. (related to a large area) differences in explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) 
 Econometric results of the participation, demand and supply of off-farm labor are presented after an initial 
 analysis of differences in the (numbers that change/things that change) affecting off-farm labor activity between areas, which are mostly due 
 to different social and farm policy governments. In terms of family, workers and location (features/ qualities/ traits), 
 New York and Ontario dairy families are almost the same (see Table 1). An (very big/very strong) number of the operators 
 are married with an average age in the mid to late 40s. Ontario families tend to be (a) little younger and a bit 
 larger with about one-third having three or more children living at home, instead of less than one-quarter of 
 New York families. The percentage of Ontario producers who left school before completing high school is more 
 than double that of New York, although a almost the same  percentage in both areas received (after high school) education. 
 Women involved in the survey are more highly educated than the men (without any concern about/having nothing to do with) area. 
 Farm (features/ qualities/ traits) represent the major difference between surveyed families. New York producers on 
 average milk nearly twice as many cows (81) as their Ontario peers (47), and the New York take from herds, in 
 general, are much larger. Nearly 75% of Ontario producers milk fewer than 51 cows, while less than half of the 
 New Yorkers milk a almost the same  number. Only 4% of Ontario dairies are 100-plus groups, whereas over 20% of New 
 York groups are of that size. Milk production per cow is also higher in New York by an average of 15%. (even though there is the existence of) 
 producing less milk, the average Ontario producer's net farm income is about 60% (US$10,000) higher 
 
 136 
 
 A. Weersink et al.j Farming-based Money flow 18 (1998) 127-143 
 
 than that (understood/made real/achieved) by the average operator in New York. Over 38% of New York farms had negative farm 
 income in 1990 (a time of (compared to other things) low US milk prices) while only 14% of Ontario farms did. Not only are 
 farm incomes higher in Ontario but they are also more (branched out/done different things) with non-milk sales about 3 times 
 higher than for New York dairies. Ontarians also have lower debt-to-valuable thing ratios (0.26 vs. 0.39). Over 65% of 
 the Ontario dairies have positive net farm incomes and debt-to-valuable thing ratios less than 0.40, whereas only 31% of 
 the New York farms are in such a good (money-related) condition. Differences in farm (money-related) position are 
 reflected in differences in happiness expressed by producers toward dairy farming. 
 (related to a large area) differences/different versions in these factors influencing off-farm employment are due to different policy governments. 
 The supply-managed marketing system for milk in Ontario secures/makes sure of operators a fair return calculated on the basis 
 of a cost of production formula. In 1991, the system created receipts per unit of milk sold that were 20% 
 higher in Ontario than New York and as a result mostly explains the above noted (related to a large area) differences in net 
 farm income. Because this system has been in place since the late 1960s, the difference in farm support policy 
 also explains the stronger valuable thing and equity position for producers in Ontario. The stronger (money-related) position 
 enjoyed by Ontario dairy families as a result of their marketing system reduces the need for off-farm income 
 relative to their partners in New York. The need for off-farm earnings is reduced further in Ontario by the 
 investment levels needed/demanded to expand production. Higher non-milk sales for Ontario dairy farms as compared to 
 those in New York is likely due to quota costs. The resulting greater (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of income sources reduces 
 the need for off-farm employment to serve as self-insurance device. Greater government support for social 
 services in Ontario, especially for medical care, may explain the larger dairy farm families noted above in 
 Ontario as the costs for caring for such as family are reduced. The presence of young children has been 
 guessed earlier to reduce the (quality of something that makes people like it or want it) of off-farm work. So, government policy has served to decrease 
 the reservation wage while increasing the not important returns to farm work, and in that way decreased the chance of 
 off-farm employment by Ontario dairy families as compared to those in New York. 
 5.2. Work portion 
 The (related to a large area) differences in factors affecting off-farm employment due to differences in policy government are 
 carried out as more of the New York farms (47%) than the Ontario farm (36%) had either a (husband or wife), an operator 
 or both employed off-farm (Table 1). In all areas, the most common situation for those families having 
 someone working off-farm was for the (husband or wife) to be the only individual with off-farm employment (49 in New 
 York, 33% of people who responded; 65 in Ontario, 27% of people who responded). The small number of operators with outside jobs 
 and the lower off-farm employment rate as compared to the national average (60% in the US) reflects the time 
 commitment needed/demanded to manage a dairy farm relative to other farm businesses/projects. 
 In general, few differences existed between average hours worked off-farm by operators and (husband or wife)s in New 
 York and Ontario. Operators in the eastern areas with off-farm jobs spent an average of 10 h less than their 
 (husband or wife)s spend in their outside jobs, while there was little difference between operator and (related to a husband or wife) off-farm 
 hours in the western areas. Total farm and off-farm labor hours were greater for operators with off-farm 
 employment than those without. There were few (related to a large area) differences in the average hours worked off-farm by 
 operators. However, New York (husband or wife)s averaged about 5 more off-farm hours per week of employment than 
 Ontario (husband or wife)s. 
 5.3. Off-farm work participation 
 The chance of off-farm employment was guessed using a bivariate probit model (Eqs. (10) and (11)) 
 that accounted for the combined participation of the operator and (husband or wife) in making this decision. The relationship-related 
 coefficient of the error term was positive, but not very different than zero at the 5% level of 
 importance. So, two univariate probit guesses were the appropriate guesses rather than a bivariate 
 
