 probit model. However, the sign and high levels of the coefficients from the univariate probit models as 
 reported in Table 3 were agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with those created by the bivariate probit model. 
 Family (features/ qualities/ traits) had more of an influence on the chance of the (husband or wife) working off the farm than 
 the operator. The number of small children reduces the chance of the (husband or wife) looking (for) off-farm employment, 
 reflecting higher opportunity costs of home production and work time with young children (Long and Jones, 
 1980). The number of older children able to assume domestic responsibilities decreases the (related to a husband or wife) reservation 
 wage and (after that) increases the chance of off-farm employment. The result related to family (information about people/combinations of different kinds of people) are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with explanation and many prior scientific studies (Alwang and Stallmann, 1992; Gould and 
 Saupe, 1989; Huffman and Lange, 1989; Woman  and Gempesaw, 1992). In contrast, the number and age 
 distribution of children does not generally have a significant effect on the participation decision for operators, 
 suggesting that children have little influence on the operator's reservation wage. Higher happiness with farm 
 life also reduces the chance of the (husband or wife) working off-farm. The greater the utility connected with 
 farming, the higher the reservation wage needed/demanded for the (husband or wife) to look (for)  employment away from the farm. 
 Although unhappiness with farm living is an driving force for off-farm employment by the (husband or wife), it had the opposite 
 (but unimportant) effect on the chance of working off-farm for the operator. 
 Workers (features/ qualities/ traits) played a big part in the off-farm employment decisions of the dairy farm 
 families sampled, especially for (husband or wife)s. A curved life-cycle pattern was found for operators. Age has a 
 
 138 
 
 A. Weersink et al.j Farming-based Money flow 18 (1998) 127-143 
 
 good effect on off-farm labor participation until 39 years after which the chance of participation 
 declines. The effect is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the findings of Sumner (1982) and Weersink (1992) for operators only 
 and of Woman  and Gempesaw (1992) and Gould and Saupe (1989) for operators making combined decisions. In 
 contrast, the chance of off-farm employment for (husband or wife)s was found to decrease with age. (related to a husband or wife) 
 participation appears to be mostly driven by the level of education. People with less than a high school 
 degree are much less likely to work off-farm than those with such a degree. The opposite happens for 
 (husband or wife)s with some post secondary education. The result is likely connected with the increase in off-farm 
 employment earning abilities connected with more education. More education could also change attitudes 
 (related to/looking at/thinking about) the relative attractiveness with off-farm work and in that way the reservation wage. In contrast to this 
 study's results for the (husband or wife) and for a majority of previous studies on operator participation, education does not 
 appear to affect the chance of off-farm work for operators. So, schooling has an unknown hit/effect on 
 the ratio of market earnings to the not important value of farm labor. 
 Farm (features/ qualities/ traits) were found to have little influence on the chance of off-farm employment with the 
 exception of the farm's (money-related) position for the operator. As expected, increases in the fixed factors of good 
 areas of land and number of milk cows reduce the chance of working off-farm, since the not important working well of 
 farm labor increases with farm size for a given wage rate. However, the results are unimportant for both 
 operator and (husband or wife). Increases in (money-related) pressures as measured by decreases in net farm income or increases 
 in the debt-to-valuable thing ratio also reduce the chance of off-farm employment. These (numbers that change/things that change) had a significant 
 effect in the operator's decision but not for the (husband or wife). Differences in farm policy between Ontario and New 
 York are reflected in the (related to a large area) values for these farm (features/ qualities/ traits). The supply management system in 
 Ontario has resulted in farms with fewer cows than those in New York, but with higher net farm income and 
 lower debt-to-valuable thing ratios. As a result, differences in farm policy have an indirect influence on the chance of 
 off-farm employment. 
 Country did not produce operator off-farm labor participation. The result may be due to including 
 farm support policy (things to carefully think about) within the farm (typical and expected) (numbers that change/things that change) discussed above. Differences in 
 social policy between New York and Ontario have not been (taken/took by force)/(taken/took control of) by previous explanatory (numbers that change/things that change). As a 
 result, the dummy (number or thing that changes) for the country in which the farm is located can account for any difference. The 
 finding that (husband or wife)s in New York were much more likely to work off-farm than their partners in 
 Ontario is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with this guess. The lack of free medical care and so the need for insurance raises 
 the relative value of earnings from off-farm employment that often include medical benefit packages. (related to a large area) 
 location did not significantly influence off-farm participation rates. The other location (number or thing that changes), distance to a 
 major centre, was found to lower the chance of off-farm employment. This was expected given that an 
 increase in travel cost will increase the reservation wage; however, the coefficient was unimportant for both 
 operator and (husband or wife). 
 5.4. Reasons for off-farm employment 
 Although the previous analysis provides an understanding of the factors affecting the decision to work off the 
 farm, a (like nothing else) aspect of the survey test/list of questions in this study is that families were asked directly for the major 
 reason why a member(s) worked off the farm. Maintaining the dairy farm business was the most often referred to 
 reason for off-farm employment of operators in both New York and Ontario (Fig. 1), which is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with 
 the econometric findings just discussed (Table 3). However, nearly half (45%) of the operators in New York 
 working off-farm said they needed that income to maintain the dairy farm business, while less than one-third 
 (29%) of the Ontario operators did so for the same reason. Over 14% of New York operators working off-farm 
 did so for the fringe benefits (often medical insurance). Under the (converted to government ownership/made nation-wide) health care system in Ontario, 
 none of the operators working off-farm did so to get fringe benefits. None of the New York operators said 
 they work at off-farm employment to make contact with other people, whereas 18% of the Ontario operators 
 pointed to/showed this was their main reason for working off-farm. Although the same percentage of New York and 
 
