 Ontario operators worked off-farm to maintain family income, a much smaller share of New York producers 
 work to add to family income or increase income (firm and steady nature/lasting nature/strength). So, it appears that off-farm employment by 
 operators is far more important for the basic needs of New York farm business and families than for those in 
 Ontario. 
 (husband or wife)s of the farm operators expressed more flexibility about their choices to work off-farm. Still, the two 
 most important reasons given by New York (husband or wife)s for having off-farm jobs were to help maintain either the 
 farm business (23%) or a minimum family income (25%). Ontario farms were not only less dependent on 
 off-farm income created by the operator to maintain the farm or family income, but also on off-farm income 
 created by the (husband or wife). Only 5% of Ontario (husband or wife)s worked off-farm to help maintain the farm and 15% to 
 help maintain family income. The two most important reasons referred to by Ontario (husband or wife)s for working off-farm 
 were to add to family income (18%) and increase income (firm and steady nature/lasting nature/strength) (16%). 
 In order to better understand the relationship between farm income and the reasons why people look (for)  off-farm 
 employment, the eight reasons asked of/presented to  the household (as shown in Fig. 1) were grouped into three categories; 
 (1) to get needs; (2) to improve living standards; and (3) reasons not related to money. Needs 
 groups maintaining either the farm business or family income. Increasing or (making steady/making firm and strong) family income along 
 with fringe benefits are carefully thought about/believed ways to improve living standards, whereas contact with other people, 
 farming not first (or most important) business and 'other' are carefully thought about/believed reasons unrelated to income. The percentage of 
 people who responded within each of the three categories of reasons was plotted against four farm income classes in Fig. 
 2. 
 The level of farm income affects why people work off-farm except when the benefit came/coming from off-farm 
 employment is unrelated to income. For farms showing net losses, 70% of the operators in New York and 50% 
 of those in Ontario worked off-farm to (accomplish or gain with effort) basic needs. Almost the same  percentages referring to this reason were 
 found in the US$0-US$19,999 income category. At the other end of the income scale, none of the operators 
 with farm incomes greater than US$40,000 in either area worked off the farm to pay for basic needs. The 
 importance of (accomplishing or gaining) needs also (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) with income levels for (husband or wife)s in both areas, but the reasons 
 tend to be more evenly distributed among the four net farm income categories. 
 
