 The results especially for the operators lend support to the view of multiple job holding as a flexible 
 (machine/method/way) to (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) to changes in the money-based (surrounding conditions) facing the household. In the case of not enough 
 farm returns, off-farm earnings provide for minimum survival/income levels. Once those are (accomplished or gained), such earnings 
 provide the opportunity to raise living standards and protect against downturns in farm income below levels 
 necessary to (accomplish or gain with effort) basic needs. In fact, Barlett (1991) watched/followed that the first (or most important) reason for a sample of 
 Kansas farmers worked off-farm was the doubt connected with farm income. Wealth effects appear 
 obvious in high income levels, where reasons other than income decide/figure out the first (or most important) reason for off-farm 
 employment. So, multiple job holding is a self-insurance activity that can reduce the effect of farm 
 income downturns in the same way that credit and insurance markets can help smooth consumption. 
 5.5. Off-farm labor demand 
 
 An off-farm labor demand equation with sample selection correction factors incorporated from the binomial 
 probit model was guessed using ordinary least squares for all (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) reporting a market wage. The wage 
 offer equation (Table 3) was guessed for the (husband or wife) only due to the small number of dairy farm operators 
 
 141 
 
 A. Weersink et al. /Agricultural Money flow 18 ( 1998) 127-143 
 
 working off the farm. Off-farm wage rate for the (husband or wife) was found to increase with age until 55 years and then 
 decrease. The curved profile, although (related to numbers) unimportant, is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) life cycle 
 patterns found by previous studies (Alwang and Stallmann, 1992; Gould and Saupe, 1989; and Huffman and 
 Lange, 1989). Those people with at least some post secondary education were found to earn significantly 
 more than other dairy farm (husband or wife)s working off-farm. This was the only significant (number or thing that changes) in the labor demand 
 equation. Although wages tended to be higher in Ontario than New York, the effect of the (related to a large area) dummy 
 (number or thing that changes) was unimportant. 
 5. 6. Off-farm labor supply equation 
 
 The previous sections examined the (features/ qualities/ traits) of those participating in off-farm employment and the 
 first (or most important) reason for that decision. We now move to examine the factors affecting the number of hours worked off 
 the farm. As with the wage demand equation, off-farm labor supply (Eqs. (12)-(15)) was guessed in two 
 stages. Wage rates were (described the future) from guesses of the labor demand equation in Table 3, and sample selection 
 correction factors were created from guesses of the chance of participation in Table 3. Resulting 
 guesses are reported in Table 4. This equation also was guessed only for the families in which the (husband or wife) 
 alone had off-farm employment (Eq. (14)). 
 Two major factors influenced the number of off-farm hours supplied by (husband or wife)s in farm families. 
